Observations

  • Customers with a credit limit of 30,000 and above have an average credit limit across all their credit cards.

  • Among the customers with a rating of 4, more than 73% of them possess a total of credit cards.

  • Among the customers who make visits to the bank personally on a yearly basis, more than 68% of them have a rating of 2 or more visits.

  • Among the customers who make online login visits to the bank on a yearly basis, more than 62% of them have a rating of 2 or more visits.

  • Among customers with a rating of 4, more than 45% of them made calls to the bank or its customer service department on a yearly basis.

Choosing optimal number of clusters¶

In [35]:
clusters = range(1, 9)
meanDistortions = []  # Create a empty list

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)  # Initialize KMeans
    model.fit(fz)  # Fit kMeans on the data
    prediction = model.predict(fz)  # Predict the model on the data
    distortion = (
        sum(np.min(cdist(fz, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1))
        / fz.shape[0]  # Find distortion
    )

    meanDistortions.append(
        distortion
    )  # Append distortion values to the empty list created above

    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "bx-")
plt.xlabel("k")  # Title of X-axis
plt.ylabel("Average Distortion")  # Title of y-axis
plt.title("Selecting k with the Elbow Method", fontsize=20)  # Title of the plot

sil_score = []  # Create empty list
cluster_list = list(range(2, 10))  # Creating a list of range from 2 to 10
for n_clusters in cluster_list:
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters)  # Initializing KMeans algorithm
    preds = clusterer.fit_predict((fz))  # Predicting on the data
    # centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_
    score = silhouette_score(fz, preds)  # Cacalculating silhouette score
    sil_score.append(score)  # Appending silhouette score to empty list created above
    print("For n_clusters = {}, silhouette score is {}".format(n_clusters, score))

plt.plot(cluster_list, sil_score)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Assuming you have the following variables:
# fz: DataFrame containing the data
# kmeans3: KMeans object with labels assigned to data points

# Adding K-means cluster labels to the original DataFrame
fz["Kmeans_clusters"] = kmeans3.labels_

# Number of clusters
num_clusters = kmeans3.n_clusters

# Create subplots for boxplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, num_clusters, figsize=(16, 6))
fig.suptitle("Boxplot of numerical variables for each cluster")

# Iterate over each cluster
for cluster_num in range(num_clusters):
    # Subset the data for the current cluster
    cluster_data = fz[fz["Kmeans_clusters"] == cluster_num]

    # Generate boxplot for each numerical variable
    sns.boxplot(data=cluster_data, ax=axes[cluster_num])

    # Set title for each subplot
    axes[cluster_num].set_title(f"Cluster {cluster_num}")

# Adjust the layout
fig.tight_layout(pad=2.0)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Findings¶

Cluster 0:

  • The customer has a very high number of total credit cards.
  • The customer's yearly visits to the bank in person are above average and moderate.
  • The customer's yearly visits or online logins are low to moderate.
  • The customer's yearly calls to the bank or customer service department are moderate.

Cluster 1:

  • The customer has an above average and moderate number of total credit cards.
  • The customer's yearly visits to the bank in person are very low.
  • The customer's yearly visits or online logins are very high.
  • The customer's yearly calls to the bank or customer service department are low.

Cluster 2:

  • The customer has a low number of total credit cards.
  • The customer's yearly visits to the bank in person are lower.
  • The customer's yearly visits or online logins are moderate.
  • The customer's yearly calls to the bank or customer service department are very high.

RECOMMENDATIONS TO THE BANK¶

  • Based on the clustering analysis above and insights obtained from the different clusters, here are some business recommendations for the bank:

*Cluster 0:

Customers in this cluster possess a high number of credit cards and have moderate levels of personal visits to the bank.
They also make moderate calls to the bank's customer service department.
  • Recommendation*: Focus on providing personalized and efficient customer service to these customers. Offer them rewards and benefits tailored to their credit card usage. Provide them with convenient online banking options to reduce the need for frequent visits to the bank.

*Cluster 1:

Customers in this cluster have an above-average number of credit cards and make very low personal visits to the bank. 
However, they have a high frequency of online logins or visits.
  • Recommendation*: Develop targeted digital marketing campaigns to engage with these customers. Promote online banking features, such as mobile banking apps and online account management tools. Offer them incentives to encourage more online transactions and usage of digital services.

*Cluster 2:

Customers in this cluster have a low number of credit cards and make fewer personal visits to the bank. However, 
they have a high number of calls to the bank's customer service department.
  • Recommendation*: Enhance the customer service experience for these customers. Streamline the call handling process and minimize wait times. Provide self-service options and online resources to address common inquiries. Offer credit card options and promotions that cater to their specific needs and preferences.
  • By tailoring marketing strategies and services to the unique characteristics of each cluster, the bank can effectively meet the needs of different customer segments. This approach can lead to increased customer satisfaction, engagement, and loyalty,ultimately driving business growth and profitability.

choose optimal value of eps and minpts¶

In [48]:
import itertools
In [49]:
# Trying values of eps between 0.1 and 1; minPts between 2 and 10

eps = np.linspace(0.1, 1, 4)
minpts = np.arange(1, 4)
In [50]:
# Create a tuple of eps and minPts using product method of itertools

hyper_list = list(itertools.product(eps, minpts))
for (eps, minpts) in hyper_list:
    dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=eps, min_samples=minpts)
    labels = dbscan.fit_predict(fz)
    score = silhouette_score(fz, labels)
    print(f"eps:{eps}; minpts:{minpts}; num_labels:{len(np.unique(labels))}; score:{score}")

BUSINESS RECOMMENDATIONS TO AllLIFE BANK¶

  • Based on the given groups and objectives, here are some business recommendations for the bank to better market to and service different customer segments:

*Group -1: Customers with High Credit Cards and Online Visits

  • Offer tailored credit card promotions and rewards programs to further incentivize and engage these customers.

  • Enhance the online banking platform with personalized features and functionalities to cater to their preference for online interactions.

  • Provide proactive customer support through online channels to ensure a seamless and convenient banking experience.

*Group 0: Customers with Low Credit Cards and Moderate Visits

  • Create targeted marketing campaigns to educate and encourage these customers to explore the benefits of additional credit card offerings.

  • Offer incentives for increasing their visit frequency to the bank, such as personalized assistance or exclusive services for in-person visits.

  • Develop user-friendly mobile banking applications to accommodate their moderate preference for online interactions.

*Group 2: Customers with Above-Average Credit Cards, High Bank Visits, and Low Online Visits

  • Provide personalized services and rewards to acknowledge their loyalty and high engagement with the bank.

  • Develop initiatives to promote the use of online banking services, such as offering tutorials, convenience features, or discounts for online transactions.

  • Ensure a seamless transition between online and in-person banking experiences to accommodate their preference for in-person interactions.

*Group 3 & 4: Customers with Low Bank Visits and Low Calls

  • Implement targeted marketing campaigns to encourage these customers to utilize bank services more frequently.

  • Offer incentives such as exclusive promotions or benefits for increasing their bank visits or engaging with customer service.

  • Improve customer service channels, including self-service options, online chatbots, and timely response to inquiries, to address their needs without requiring phone calls.

  • These recommendations should help the bank better understand and cater to the diverse segments of existing customers based on their spending patterns and past interactions. It is essential to continually analyze and adapt these strategies based on customer feedback and evolving preferences to ensure a positive customer experience and maximize customer retention.
